metadata.name: coalescence #196
metadata.description:
coalescence is a real-time interactive particle system. Tens of thousands of agents of multiple distinct species interact, cooperate, and compete with one another. Each agent leaves a trail as it moves, and reacts to the trails left behind by other agents, creating complex emergent structures.

Click and drag to erase trails, forcing the agents to rebuild their patterns anew.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

You can use the url parameter "resolution" to set a fixed simulation resolution, e.g. "?resolution=4096". This can be used to capture high-quality screenshots.

metadata.name: Charcoal Seeds #280
metadata.description:
As a fundamental element derived from organic matter, charcoal happens to be at the core of all life forms. It is also the tool for artists that dates back to the most ancient times. 
By using charcoal as the the primary medium for the exhibition ‘Organic Matr’ (and resulting series of physical pieces created in collaboration with Brooklyn-based lab ArtMatr), the works creates bonds between technology and the rawest tool that was touched by the human hand, and highlights how the cycle of life is also the cycle of regeneration of matter.

Since the generative process _that uses programming code and the intervention of randomness_ was used to design the physical pieces, the long-form generative series Charcoal Seeds is a natural way to seamlessly extend back into the digital realm the ideas of matter and physicality, while showing the elements at work in the creation process. 
In each iteration a virtual seed will encapsulates the essence of organic forms and patterns. The graphic style itself tries to convey the organic feeling of tools and materials such as chalk, ink, paintbrushes. 


—— 

- "Charcoal Seeds" offers a WYSIWYG experience : by deriving the randomness from the minter’s wallet address, it is guaranteed that what you see onscreen after adjusting the params will be your actual NFT. 
However, we wanted to allow the possibility of getting some rare features. By selecting "random" for the Format or the Paper color, you will get a chance to mint a Pink or a Back background, or have a Wide Landscape format. Beware : this will break the WYSIWYG ( but it will keep your params settings safe ) 

- As usual, the project is plottable : press [s] in live mode to generate a SVG file suited for pen plotters.

- By adding a ‘scale’ parameter in the live URL, you can generate a higher resolution image. The scale ranges from 1 to 10 with a default value of 3.

metadata.name: Blooming dancers #92
metadata.description:
Inspired by the similarity between a dancer's dress and a blooming flower.

It's an homage to art and nature, with exclusive features including :

- A choice between 12 modern and 12 rarer Artist inspired color palettes (Thanks to http://www.colorlisa.com/)
- 1 to 5 dancers
- Various Soft and Hard framing options
- A unique full canvas system which allows the collector to display on portrait, landscape or square screen the art
- A lot of line and background style variations.

The art is better viewed in full screen, captures don't display the fine details

patxol - 2022

Made with p5js

metadata.name: Fabrics #887
metadata.description:
Fabric. A collection of swatches. 

This is a project of stacked PNGs producing fabric swatches. Some are almost plaids, others are more batik, while others are more of a "magic eye" or optical illusion look. 

The PNGs were generated using VBA and conditional formatting in MS Excel, then copy/pasted as an image into MS PowerPoint, and occasionally further manipulated in different image editors including MS Paint. Images were batch resized to match each other at 1125x1125.

There are a lot of options for this collection. The layers and total number of options per (included "none" layers):
- Base
    - 42
- Flecking 
    - 18
- Broad
    - 50
- Underpin
    - 43
- Warp
    - 21
- Weft
    - 26
- Overpins
    - 43
- Mask
    - 21
- Texture
    - 14


There is a slight potential to mint the "imaginary fabric", one which is comprised of only "none" layers. That is the best of the bunch, because it is only limited by your imagination. Consider it the legendary.

There should be an interplay between the coded elements of each individual PNG and the overall stack. The randomness of coded layers stacked with other, dissimilar (base) coded layers generates interesting, and at times, colorful patterns that don't have a singular, obvious, overarching algo.

Hope you enjoy! 

Stacking achieved using PureSpider's pfp code https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

License CC BY-SA 4.0

metadata.name: the centre cannot hold #94
metadata.description:
The spiral is one of the earliest symbols used by humans, found in cave paintings and petroglyphs, and is thought by some researchers to have been inspired by shamanic rituals and hallucinogenic experiences. 

The spiral is found in our mathematics via the golden ratio, and in our aesthetics via the Fibonacci Spiral, aka the Golden Spiral. Spirals are found throughout the natural world, from the shape of our galaxy, to hurricane storms in our atmosphere, to seashells in the oceans.   

Spirals are also used to conceptualize entropy, spiraling out of control, the downward spiral from order into chaos. Each of these works represents this form of spiral, with varying degrees of chaos versus order, a formerly-cohesive group throwing off parts of itself due to overwhelming centrifugal force.   
--  
Uses p5js (LGPL-2.1). Color palettes are inspired by the paintings of Mondrian, Rafael, Van Gogh, Munch, O'Keefe, and Magritte.
